ce:section.ce:para:
Ciprofloxacin (CIP) is a quinolone antibiotic drug, and its unreasonable abuse and improper disposal of residues will lead to accumulation in the environment and animal products, causing drug resistance and adverse effects on human health(

                        Bacanlı & Başaran, 2019

                     ). In 2019, the Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Affairs, the National Health Commission and the State Administration for Market Regulation of China jointly issued GB 31650–2019 “National Food Safety Standard Maximum Residue Limits for Veterinary Drugs in Foods”(

                        Bureau, 2021

                     ). The document clearly stipulates the use of antibiotics as veterinary drugs. Although there are strict regulations on the use of antibiotics at home and abroad, the detection methods for antibiotic residues can't achieve effective detection, especially for soup samples with complex components such as hot pot and malatang, and other samples with complex ingredients.

At present, the detection methods for antibiotic drug residues include high performance liquid chromatography (HPLC)(

                        Peris-Vicente, Iborra-Millet, Albiol-Chiva, Carda-Broch, & Esteve-Romero, 2019

                     ), liquid chromatography-mass spectrometry (LC-MS)(Zheng et al., 2019), etc. However, these methods rely on expensive detection instruments and are time-consuming. Especially for the detection of malatang samples, many interference factors caused by complex ingredients make analysis harder. Even worse, improper sample handling may cause severe damage to HPLC or LC-MS. To the best of our knowledge, the national standard for detection of antibiotic residues in malatang has not been issued, remaining a problem to be solved. Hence, there is a pressing need to establish an efficient, handy and economical method to detect antibiotic residues for practical purpose.

Carbon dots (CDs) are a class of nanomaterials with unique optical and chemical properties. They have good biocompatibility, low toxicity and excellent photostability, making them ideal candidates for bioimaging, drug delivery and biosensing. In recent years, CDs as fluorescent probes for drug detection has attracted wide attention. Cai et al.(Cai et al., 2023) used 8-hydroxyjulolidine and citrate as carbon sources to prepare red CDs as a probe to detect malachite green in fish specimens. Tong et al.(

                        Tong, Lin, Duan, Wang, & Wu, 2022

                     ) used multicolor carbon dots combined with aptamers and MoS2 sheets to visually analyze sulfamethazine, oxytetracycline and chloramphenicol in aquatic products. The corresponding detection limits were 0.47, 0.48, and 0.34 ng/mL, respectively. Cui et al.(

                        Cui et al., 2022

                     ) synthesized NIR-CDs using polyethyleneimine and glutathione as raw materials via a one-step hydrothermal method, whose fluorescence can be quenched by aptamer and then recovered by CIP through electrostatic interaction between positively charged carbon dots and negatively charged CIP aptamers. The detection limit of the CDs for CIP is 0.167 ng/mL. Lu et al.(Lu et al., 2020) used selenium-containing yeast as raw material to synthesize carbon dots by a hydrothermal method. The carbon dots were further coupled with riboflavin to form a dual-emitting probe for CIP with a detection limit of 0.13 μM. Yadav et al.(

                        Yadav, Choudhary, & Paital, 2024

                     ) developed a composite material (CD@OMC@NH2) composed of CDs and ordered mesoporous carbon, which showed a highly selective response to nitrofurantoin and furazolidone with fluorescence quenching. Lu et al.(W. Lu, Guo, Yue, Zhang, Fan, 
                        Li et al., 2023

                     ) prepared Mo-CDs by hydrothermal method using (NH4)6Mo7O24·4H2O and ascorbic acid as precursors. Based on the Mo-CDs nanozyme catalytic system, a colorimetric sensor for detecting ampicillin was developed, with detection range of 0.500–100 μg/mL. Deng et al.(Deng et al., 2024) applied antioxidant carbon dots (ACD) prepared with citric acid, ethylenediamine and L-arginine to the detection of bleomycin based on the dynamic quenching response mechanism. The detection limit for bleomycin was 0.58 μg/mL. However, these carbon dot-based fluorescent probes are either in the “off” mode, with low specificity and sensitivity, or need to be combined with other materials.

Considering the complex composition of milk and Malatang, the proteins and lipids in them may affect the binding of N, P-CDs to antibiotics, thereby affecting the accuracy of the detection(

                           Zhang, Bao, Qian, Zhou, & Zhang, 2022

                        ). Therefore, the sample needs to be pretreated to remove proteins and lipids. First, 10% trichloroacetic acid was mixed with the milk samples and then ultrasonicated for 30 min to remove proteins according to the method of Liang et al.(Liang et al., 2022). Subsequently, the samples were placed in a 65 °C water bath for 30 min to remove lipids according to the method of Poshteh Shirani et al.(

                           Poshteh Shirani, Rezaei, & Ensafi, 2019

                        ). Then centrifuged for 30 min in a centrifuge at 3000 r/min to obtain a clear solution, which is used as a sample to be tested. The same pretreatment process was applied for Malatang soup. This pretreatment step helps reduce the impact of proteins and lipids and ensure more accurate and reliable experimental results.

CA was employed as the carbon source, MPD as the nitrogen source, and phosphoric acid as both the phosphorus source and acid donor to synthesize N, P-CDs in absolute ethanol by a microwave-assisted approach at 180 °C for a duration of 30 min. The UV absorption of N, P-CDs was tested using a UV–visible spectrophotometer, and its fluorescence properties were studied using fluorescence spectra. We observed a noteworthy phenomenon in our study. As the solution is diluted, the fluorescence color of the N, P-CDs changes from yellow to green (Fig. S1). Additionally, the fluorescence intensity steadily increases and the emission wavelength progressively shifts towards the blue region, as illustrated in Fig. S2. The increased fluorescence and blue-shifted emission phenomena going with decreasing of concentration of N, P-CDs may be due to the reduced inhibition of π-π interactions and the induced redistribution of electrons(

                           Ba et al., 2020

                        ). This concentration effect causes N, P-CDs to behave aggregation quenching and severe self-absorption at higher concentrations. That is, the fluorescence intensity is inversely proportional to the concentration(J. 

                           Li & Gong, 2022

                        ). In order to verify that the fluorescence is from the prepared N, P-CDs rather than raw material, we measured the UV absorption of CA, MPD, and N, P-CDs respectively. As shown in Fig. 1a, it is obvious that the UV absorption peaks of the three are different. N, P-CDs have an absorption peak at 444 nm different from the other two raw materials, which confirms new substance formed.

Phosphoric acid can provide P, at the same time, it is also an acid. To elucidate the role of phosphoric acid in fluorescence enhancement of N, P-CDs, we further prepared a series of CDs from CA, MPD as main sources: N-CDs (without additional dopants), Na3PO4-CDs (with Na3PO4 as dopant), H2SO4-CDs (with H2SO4 as dopant), HNO3-CDs (with HNO3 as dopant), H3BO3-CDs (with H3BO3 as dopant). Their fluorescence spectra are shown in Fig. 1d. We first compare the fluorescence spectra of N-CDs, Na3PO4-CDs, N, P-CDs. It is worth noting that N-CDs have an emission peak at a shorter wavelength (434 nm) with a shoulder peak at about 475 nm. Na3PO4-CDs show a little red shift in fluorescence (445 nm and 490 nm). The emission peak of N, P-CDs drastically red-shifts to 519 nm and fluorescence intensity significantly increases. Then we compare the fluorescence spectra of N, P-CDs, H2SO4-CDs, HNO3-CDs, H3BO3-CDs and Na3PO4-CDs. It is noticed that N, P-CDs, H2SO4-CDs, HNO3-CDs, H3BO3-CDs all show red-shifted emission comparing to Na3PO4-CDs, indicating the acid effect. Among the six samples, N, P-CDs show largest wavelength and the highest fluorescence intensity. The emission peaks of N, P-CDs, H2SO4-CDs, HNO3-CDs, H3BO3-CDs are at 519 nm, 487 nm, 486 nm and 491 nm. These observations indicate that, on one hand, phosphoric acid plays the role of heteroatom dopants, on the other hand, serves as acid. The synergetic effect of phosphoric acid induces long wavelength emission and high fluorescence intensity. UV–visible absorption spectrum also shows the similar effect (Fig. 1e). It is noticeable that an absorption peak at 450 nm appears for N, P-CDs. This further proves that the P element and the acidic environment provided by phosphoric acid have a significant impact on the yellow luminescence of N, P-CDs. The picture of N-CDs, Na3PO4-CDs, N, P-CDs, H2SO4-CDs, HNO3-CDs, and H3BO4-CDs under sunlight and UV are shown in Fig. S3. The quantum yield of the prepared N, P-CDs (43.67%) is much higher than N-CDs (11.06%), Na3PO4-CDs (13.78%), H2SO4-CDs (8.34%), HNO3-CDs (3.27%), and H3BO4-CDs (17.89%). The QY of N, P-CDs shows that the addition of phosphoric acid has made an outstanding contribution to the improvement of the quantum yield of CDs. The higher quantum yield of N, P-CDs can be explained from three aspects. First, m-phenylenediamine is an aromatic compound tending to form sp2 carbon clusters. Second, m-phenylenediamine is a common nitrogen source. The N element introduced into the carbon dots can generate more amino active groups, thereby increasing the quantum yield of N, P-CDs(Luo et al., 2018). Third, the oxidizing property of phosphoric acid causes defect sites on the surface of N, P-CDs. The synergistic effect of active groups, surface defect sites and sp2 carbon clusters effectively increases the band gap in the ultraviolet region, resulting in brighter fluorescence and higher quantum yield(
                        Peng et al., 2012
                        ).

Fig. 2a shows the UV, excitation and emission spectra of N, P-CDs. The UV absorption band at 235 nm belongs to the n-s* transition of C-NH2 or C-OH. The ultraviolet absorption band at 261 nm belongs to the π-π* transition of the conjugated system CC. The peak at 444 nm may be the conjugated structure of the aromatic ring with amino and phosphate groups. We tested the fluorescence spectrum of N, P-CDs at 370–490 nm excitation (interval 20 nm) (Fig. 2b) and found that N, P-CDs show red shift trend with higher wavelength excitation. It is said that there is a series of emission traps between the π state and π* state of N, P-CDs(

   Sahu, Behera, Maiti, & Mohapatra, 2012

). Therefore, as the excitation wavelength changes, emission traps with different surface states dominate respectively, thereby showing excitation wavelength dependence. It can be seen that when the excitation wavelength is 470 nm, the fluorescence intensity of N, P-CDs is the highest, and the emission peak position is at 541 nm. N, P-CDs show bright yellow fluorescence under 365 nm ultraviolet light.

The Fourier transform infrared spectrum of N, P-CDs and N-CDs is shown in Fig. 3a. The peak appearing at 3273 cm−1 is attributed to the stretching vibration of NH and OH, and the peak at 2974 cm−1 represents CH. The stretching vibration of CC and CO in the aromatic ring causes obvious peaks at 1639 cm−1 and 1512 cm−1 respectively in the infrared spectrum(L.


                           song, Cui, Zhang, Hu, & Liu, 2016

                        ; Y. 

                           Song et al., 2017

                        ). In addition, the peaks appearing at 978 cm−1 is attributed to the stretching vibration of P-O-R. The stretching vibration of PO4
                        3− results in a peak at 483 cm-1(

                           Parvin & Mandal, 2017

                        ; 

                           Shi et al., 2016

                        ). This is very obviously different from the infrared spectrum of N-CDs, and also proves that P is successfully doped into N, P-CDs.

To elucidate the elemental composition of N, P-CDs in detail, XPS analyses were carried out. As depicted in Fig. 3b, the XPS survey revealed four distinctive peaks centered at 284.8 eV, 134.58 eV, 402 eV, and 532.92 eV, corresponding to the presence of carbon (C, 20.59%), phosphorus (P, 16.62%), nitrogen (N, 2.92%), and oxygen (O, 59.87%). The high-resolution C1s spectrum, as shown in Fig. 3c, exhibited peaks at 284.6 eV, 286.1 eV, and 287.9 eV, signifying the presence of C=C/C-C, C-N/C-O/C-P, and CO functionalities, respectively(Ananthanarayanan et al., 2015). Meanwhile, the high-resolution N1s XPS spectrum (Fig. 3d) displayed two discernible peaks at 400.6 eV and 401.8 eV, indicative of N-H/pyrrole N(

                           Zhao, Li, Zhang, An, & Sun, 2019

                        ) and N-X (X = C, O, P)(Song et al., 2017) respectively. The O1s XPS spectrum (Fig. 3e) manifested two peaks at 530.9 eV and 532.4 eV, corresponding to CO and CO /P=O groups, respectively. The P2p XPS spectrum of N, P-CDs (Fig. 3f) revealed the presence of PO (133.1 eV) and P-C/P-N (134.1 eV) moieties [43]. The FTIR and XPS characterizations provide compelling evidence of the successful incorporation of both phosphorus and nitrogen within the structure of N, P-CDs.

In order to decide the sensitivity of N, P-CDs to CIP detection, we mixed N, P-CDs with a series of concentration gradient (0–30 μM) CIP solutions under optimized detection conditions. Fluorescence spectra were characterized and fluorescence intensity was recorded. A linear relationship between (FF0)/F0 and CIP concentration was formed. As shown in Fig. 5a, as the CIP concentration increases, the fluorescence intensity of N, P-CDs gradually increases. The standard linear equation corresponding to N, P-CDs is (FF0)/F0 = 0.1675CCIP + 0.6603, R2 = 0.9945 in the range of 0.5–25 μM (Fig. 5b). The limit of detection is calculated according to the standard 3σ rule(

                           Qian, Xu, Jiang, Wang, & Lin, 2019

                        ) (LOD = 3σ/k), and the result is 24.2 nM. We compared our LOD result with literatures. As shown in Table.S1, N, P-CDs can achieve good detection performance. Comparing with other materials, N, P-CDs is pure carbon materials and efficiently synthesized by microwave-assisted method without additional modification or tedious column chromatographyseparationm.

The surface of N, P-CDs features functional groups including -OH, -COOH, PO. These groups interact with the CN, CO, and -OH groups of CIP, giving rise to robust intermolecular hydrogen bonds. These interactions serve to bolster the fluorescence of N, P-CDs(Yang et al., 2014). In order to verify this conjecture, we conducted further research to exclude the inherent fluorescence of CIP. We measured the fluorescence intensities of N, P-CDs, CIP, and the N, P-CDs-CIP with an excitation wavelength of 470 nm. Fig. 6a shows that the fluorescence intensity of CIP is very weak, and N, P-CDs show obvious fluorescence while N, P-CDs-CIP show much enhanced fluorescence due to addition of CIP. Simultaneously, N, P-CDs-CIP emit a brighter yellow fluorescence under 365 nm UV, affirming that the fluorescence enhancement in the mixed system is not from CIP itself but rather the consequence of intermolecular hydrogen bond between the N, P-CDs and CIP. We also compared the infrared spectra of N, P-CDs and N, P-CDs-CIP. The FTIR spectrum of N, P-CDs-CIP shows (Fig. 6b) that C-OH stretching vibration at about 3241 cm−1, which is shifted by 38 cm−1 compared to that of N, P-CDs (3273 cm−1). The observed shift can be attributed to the establishment of hydrogen bonds, which exert the effect of elongating chemical bonds (Li et al., 2023). The frequency of stretching vibrations in chemical bonds is inversely proportional to the square root of the bond length, leading to a concomitant decrease in wavenumber(Wang et al., 2021). Further again, we examined ultraviolet absorption of N, P-CDs and N, P-CDs-CIP. From the UV absorption spectrum (Fig. 6c), the UV absorption of N, P-CDs-CIP has characteristic absorption peaks at 228 nm and 435 nm. Compared with the characteristic absorption peaks of N, P-CDs (236 nm and 444 nm), there is an obvious shift (Δδ1 = 8 nm, Δδ2 = 9 nm). The notable blue shift in the absorption bands is commonly associated with the formation of hydrogen bonds(L. 

                           Li et al., 2023

                        ). The establishment of intermolecular hydrogen bonds diminishes the mechanical characteristics of hydroxyl chemical bonds, leading to a shift in the absorption frequency towards shorter wavelength(Liu, Ma, 

                           Yuan & Huang, 2004

                        ). In summary, the augmented fluorescence of N, P-CDs induced by CIP is likely attributable to the formation of intermolecular hydrogen bonds resulting from their interaction.

To elucidate the detection mechanism of N, P-CDs to pH, we conducted a study involving the UV–vis and fluorescence spectrum of N, P-CDs at varying pH levels. Fig. 8b and c are the UV absorption spectra and fluorescence spectra of N, P-CDs at pH 2 and 12 under 470 nm excitation. It is evident that in comparison to pH 2, the UV absorption peak of N, P-CDs at pH 12 shows a blue shift from 235 nm to 231 nm, and the fluorescence emission also shifts towards the blue spectrum, transitioning from 527 nm to 510 nm. We speculate that that N, P-CDs have the capacity to absorb hydroxide ions (OH−), thereby passivating the surface defects of carbon dots, and concurrently establishing a protective “shell” encapsulating the carbon dots. The presence of this “shell” mitigates the non-radiative recombination rate by effectively insulating the carbon dots from the external environment(

                           Chandra et al., 2012

                        ), ultimately leading to the enhancement of their fluorescence. Simultaneously, this “shell” also results in a reduction in the particle size of the carbon dots, leading to a blue shift in their emission due to the quantum size effect (

                           Kong et al., 2014

                        ).
